{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636515"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17589"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17589"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.4,0.05,0.3,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10279"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56879"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10079"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24017"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucose 6-phosphate is formed when glucose enters cells and is phosphorylated by hexokinase or glucokinase.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a property of glucose 6-phosphate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Is directly converted to glycogen","Requires energy to form from glucose 1-phosphate","Freely diffuses between cells","Can only enter glycolysis pathway","Cannot cross cell membranes freely"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eglucose 6-phosphate is that it cannot cross cell membranes freely\u003C/strong\u003E due to its negatively charged phosphate group. This traps glucose inside cells after phosphorylation, ensuring it remains available for cellular metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECan only enter glycolysis pathway\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose 6-phosphate can enter multiple pathways including glycolysis, pentose phosphate pathway, and glycogen synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIs directly converted to glycogen\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose 6-phosphate must first be converted to glucose 1-phosphate and then UDP-glucose before glycogen synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires energy to form from glucose 1-phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E - The conversion between glucose 1-phosphate and glucose 6-phosphate is catalysed by phosphoglucomutase and does not require energy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFreely diffuses between cells\u003C/strong\u003E - The phosphate group prevents membrane crossing\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis property of glucose 6-phosphate is important for maintaining glucose gradients and regulating cellular metabolism. Only the liver contains glucose 6-phosphatase which can remove the phosphate group, allowing glucose release into the bloodstream.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glucose 6-phosphate is a key metabolic intermediate that can enter either glycolysis or the pentose phosphate pathway.","Glucose 6-phosphate cannot freely cross cell membranes due to its phosphate group.","The liver contains glucose 6-phosphatase which allows it to release free glucose into the bloodstream."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Available from: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56879"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17589"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56879"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T12:36:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T12:36:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10279"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71400"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},